        "user": "What is a transformer (architecture)?",
        "assistant": "# Transformer Architecture\n\nThe **Transformer** is a deep learning architecture introduced in the 2017 paper *\"Attention Is All You Need\"* by Vaswani et al. It revolutionized natural language processing and now underpins most modern AI models, including GPT, BERT, and Claude.\n\n## Core Innovation: Self-Attention\n\nUnlike previous architectures (RNNs, LSTMs) that process sequences one token at a time, Transformers process **all tokens in parallel** using a mechanism called **self-attention**. This allows each token to directly \"attend to\" every other token in the sequence, regardless of distance.\n\n## Key Components\n\n### 1. Self-Attention Mechanism\nFor each token, three vectors are computed:\n- **Query (Q)** – what the token is looking for\n- **Key (K)** – what the token offers\n- **Value (V)** – the actual content\n\nAttention is computed as:\n$$\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right)V$$\n\n### 2. Multi-Head Attention\nMultiple attention operations run in parallel, letting the model capture different types of relationships (syntactic, semantic, positional) simultaneously.\n\n### 3. Positional Encodings\nSince the model has no inherent sense of order, position information is added to the token embeddings (via sinusoidal functions or learned embeddings).\n\n### 4. Feed-Forward Networks\nEach position passes through a small fully-connected network applied independently.\n\n### 5. Residual Connections + Layer Normalization\nThese stabilize training and allow very deep networks.\n\n## Original Architecture\n\nThe original Transformer had two parts:\n- **Encoder** – processes input (used in models like BERT)\n- **Decoder** – generates output autoregressively (used in models like GPT)\n\nModern variants often use only one:\n- **Encoder-only** (BERT) – good for understanding/classification\n- **Decoder-only** (GPT, Claude, LLaMA) – good for generation\n- **Encoder-decoder** (T5, original Transformer) – good for translation/summarization\n\n## Why It Matters\n\n- **Parallelizable**: Trains efficiently on GPUs/TPUs\n- **Scales well**: Performance keeps improving with more data and parameters\n- **Captures long-range dependencies** better than RNNs\n- **General-purpose**: Now used for text, images (Vision Transformers), audio, code, and more\n\nThe Transformer is essentially the foundation of the current era of large language models and generative AI.",
